One America, two kinds of citizens
New York – As I write this, officials across the United States are still counting votes from the 2020 US presidential election.
Once the results are finally determined, recounts and legal challenges are bound to follow.
In this closely contested election with record-high voter turnout, that is to be expected.
Only American citizens can vote for the president, but that choice affects people all over the world.
If it is too early to determine the election results, it is not too early to consider what this election portends for the world's most powerful nation.
On the positive side, the United States remains a strong democratic country.
Despite actual constraints related to the pandemic, voter turnout was still high.
The process seems to be unfolding as planned.
And violence has been rare.
Courts are investigating decisions by the US Postal Service that seem to be politically motivated and hinder the transportation of ballots expected to come primarily from Democratic-leaning areas.
US President Donald Trump announced victory without evidence late Tuesday night, and his call to stop counting votes (at least in the states where he was leading) appears to have fallen on deaf ears.
However, it is concerning that there is still a large divide among American voters.
The two candidates received nearly equal numbers of votes.
It is not surprising that this division could lead to a divided government.
If the current trend continues, the Democrats will win the White House and continue to control the House of Representatives, while the Republicans will retain control of the Senate.
Governorships and state legislative seats are nearly evenly split between the two parties (with Republicans slightly ahead).
The Democratic expected "blue wave" did not materialize.
Biden is likely to win the popular vote by a significant margin, securing around four to five million more votes out of nearly 160 million cast.
But Republicans held onto several seats in the Senate that many had predicted would flip, while Democrats actually lost seats in the House.
This result does not stem from strong authorizations or political realignments.
Trump’s poll numbers are very good, with over 5 million more votes than in 2016, making him the second-highest vote-getter in U.S. presidential history and surpassing any previous winner.
Notably, this occurred against the backdrop of record-high daily coronavirus cases and deaths exceeding 1,000.
Just as the consequences of his administration’s mishandling of the pandemic were becoming most severe, nearly half of voters turned to support him.
Even if Trump loses, which seems likely, he will still hold significant sway, especially if he continues to remain in the public eye (which also seems likely).
Even if he does not run himself, Trump is likely to have a substantial influence on the Republican nominee for the 2024 election.
The Republican party will be far removed from the parties of presidents Bush or Reagan.
Trumpism – a form of modern American populism – will remain a powerful force.
Not surprisingly, despite lacking any evidence, Trump has tried to portray himself as virtuous and legitimate, seeking to undermine the legitimacy of the election results and accusing them of fraud.
Many of his supporters will refuse to accept Biden’s legitimacy as president.
Trump is likely never to concede or attend the inauguration of his successor.
In the words of Will Rogers, Trump has never met a norm he couldn't break.
Americans are living in increasingly separate worlds.
They sort themselves into different communities and regions based on shared views.
And each world tends to watch its own cable channels, listen to its own radio stations and podcasts, and visit its own websites.
And the lack of a national civics course facilitates the division among people of different generations.
It is worth noting that division within the country is typically not along economic lines.
People from all strata voted for both candidates, and the voting patterns based on demographics, gender, and race did not align as many had predicted.
Their disagreements primarily revolve around remedies.
Education level is clearly an indicator of political orientation, as is geography. Republican voters tend to live in exurbs and rural areas, while Democrats prefer urban areas.
However, culture may play a larger role in American politics than any other factor.
In fact, foreign policy did not seem particularly important in the campaign, except for mobilizing specific districts, such as the large Cuban and Venezuelan communities in South Florida.
Given this context, it is difficult to gain public support for major reforms to the presidential election or government operations.
This situation is akin to reforming the UN Security Council.
Many believe that the current system is seriously flawed and lacks representation, but consensus on reform is unlikely because any potential solution would benefit some while harming others.
It is not surprising that those who stand to lose from the changes will resist them.
This will make governance difficult.
This will largely depend on Senate Republican Leader Mitch McConnell's assessment and his ability and willingness to cooperate with the subsequent Biden presidency.
Cooperation will also require Biden to make compromises, which will certainly be resisted by more ideologically driven members of his own party.
Democrats have tried to reject Trump and everything he stands for in sharp terms.
But they were not successful.
The Republicans sought an election that would validate Trump.
And that did not happen either.
Instead, the election revealed a nation and two types of citizens.
They will have to coexist; whether they can do so remains to be seen.
